method.description:
Message attributes:

@filename (symbol, default: none): filename

@dpi (int, default: 72): Dots Per Inch

@width (double, default: none): Width In Coordinates

@height (double, default: none): Height In Coordinates

@pixelwidth (double, default: none): Width In Pixels

@pixelheight (double, default: none): Height In Pixels

@center (llll, default: none): Center Coordinates

@zoom (llll, default: none): Zoom Percentage



Saves the object as a PNG image. Optional argument provides the filename (otherwise a dialog box will pop up).

The word exportpng, followed by an file path, exports the current canvas as a PNG image.
This can be further followed by a list formatted as:
(specification value) (specification value).... 

Each specification can be one of the followings: 

• "dpi": the value is expected to be the dpi resolution of the exported image; 

• "width": the value is expected to be the width of the exported image in pixels; 

• "height": the value is expected to be the height of the exported image in pixels; 

• "center": the value is expected to be an llll containing the coordinates of the center;

The word random sets the state of some random cells to 1, by default setting all other cells to 0. The word can be further followed by a list formatted as: (specification value) (specification value)....
Each specification can be one of the followings:
• "distribution": the value is expected to be either "gaussian" or "uniform";
• "density": the floating point density of cells for the distribution;
• "append": set 1 if you need to append the random cells to the existing cells, set 0 if you need to replace all current cells with random cells.

Any portion of C code is considered the code for a custom rule to be implemented.
This code is run for every cell, and should return the new state of the cell
(in the typical 1-bit case: 1 if the cell will be alive at the next generation, 0 otherwise).
Knowing that a t_cell is defined as: 

typedef unsigned char t_cell; 

some variables can be used inside the code: 

• cell: a t_cell containing the current state of the cellM 

• neighbors_size: an int containing the neighbors size; 

• neighbors: an double array of neighbors_size by neighbors_size cells containing each a t_cell element; 

• sum_neighbors: the sum of all the value of the neighbors of the current cell; 

• nonzero_neighbors: the number of all the non-zero neighbors of the current cell. 

More precisely, the prototype of the function being written is thus: 

t_cell life_customstep_one(t_cell cell, int neighbors_size, t_cell **neighbors, int sum_neighbors, int nonzero_neighbors); 

This code is compiled on the fly, so that users can take advantage of native speed for complex rules.

attribute.description:
s Sets the mapping between cell values and corresponding color: 

None: no mapping: cell color is always the one defined by cellcolor; 

Candycane: colors are chosen via the candycane; 

Color Scale: cell color is the one defined by cellcolor, but rescaled so that it is lighter for small cells value (range is from 1 to mapmax); 

Color Spectrum: cell color ranges from red to violet (for cells values from 1 to mapmax);

Random: cell color is chosen randomly;

Custom: cell color is defined via cellred, cellgreen, cellblue, cellalpha.

Toggles the ability to display the pitches by coloring the cells background. Three modes are available:
Don't: don't show notes as colors; 

Colors: show notes as colors red to violet (the defined minpitch is mapped to red, the defined maxpitch is mapped to violet,
anything in between is interpolated; anything beyond is clipped); 

Wrapped Colors: show notes as colors, where the color spectrum correspond to each musical octave, and octaves are mapped to different saturation.

Toggles the way in which velocities are displayed: 

None: velocities are not displayed; 

Transparency: small velocities are mapped on more transparent colors; 

Lightness: small velocities are mapped on lighter colors; 

Darkness: small velocities are mapped on darker colors.
